headline: Nasdaq Falls as Worries Mount on Jobs and AI Valuations
summary: A slide in big tech shares led a broad selloff Thursday, spurred by weak economic data and renewed concerns about the dizzying rally in artificial-intelligence shares.  All three major indexes notched declines, with investors starting to get nervous again that AI shares have run up too far, too fast, and that companies are ramping up their spending despite a darkening picture of the jobs market.  The chip maker has lost about $457 billion in market value since Monday’s close of trading, its largest loss in market value over a three-session stretch since January’s DeepSeek-driven tech selloff, according to Dow Jones Market Data.

Another requirement is for Tesla to roll out one million AI-powered robots - despite the fact it hasn't released a single one so far.

summary:
STORY: :: Tesla shareholders applaud as CEO Elon Musk's $878 billion pay package is approved

"...On the 2025 CEO Performance Award to our founder and CEO, Elon Musk, with over 75% voting in favor.... approved!" 

:: November 6, 2025

:: Austin, Texas

Shares of Tesla rose about 2% in after-hours trading. The proposal was approved with over 75% support.

The vote, analysts have said, is a positive for Tesla's stock, whose valuation hangs on Musk's vision of making vehicles drive themselves, expanding robotaxis across the U.S. and selling humanoid robots, even though his far-right political rhetoric has hurt the Tesla brand this year.
